The paper deals with the problem of detecting outlier pairs of strongly correlated variables among a collection of n variables with otherwise weak pairwise correlations. This problem involves geometric tasks and matrix multiplication, which are typical topics in computational geometry (cs.CG) and theoretical computer science (cs.CC). The paper also presents corollaries for learning sparse Boolean functions and the light bulb problem, which are related to machine learning (cs.LG) and information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper uses techniques such as randomized algorithms and matrix multiplication, which are common in data structures (cs.DS).
